00:09:52.764 --> 00:09:59.234
from DNA records to telephone records to photos to CCTV footage, even through

00:09:59.234 --> 00:10:03.784
to the fact that most cities have abundant street lighting so it’s easier

00:10:03.784 --> 00:10:08.084
to see what’s going on at night, none of this existed in the medieval era.

00:10:08.684 --> 00:10:12.774
There had to be eye-witnesses to the crime being committed, and

00:10:13.054 --> 00:10:17.414
even that was often a case of one person’s word against another’s.

00:10:18.504 --> 00:10:23.874
So, although it was ripe for bias and would certainly have led to many

00:10:23.904 --> 00:10:26.914
innocent people being found guilty because their neighbours didn’t

00:10:26.914 --> 00:10:31.094
like them or because they were a bit strange, it was a step forward.

00:10:32.484 --> 00:10:36.904
And what happened if someone was deemed to be guilty of a crime, you might ask?

00:10:37.724 --> 00:10:44.414
Well, the punishments became harsher, especially for crimes that challenged royal authority.

00:10:45.794 --> 00:10:51.484
Execution–the death penalty–was used more frequently, and new laws,

00:10:51.534 --> 00:10:55.684
like “forest laws”, were introduced to protect royal hunting grounds.

00:10:56.744 --> 00:11:02.994
Killing a deer from the king’s land could result in brutal punishments—sometimes even death.

00:11:04.344 --> 00:11:08.964
Now, these laws weren’t just about stopping people from stealing deer;

00:11:09.564 --> 00:11:14.144
rather, they were a signal to everyone of the absolute power of the

00:11:14.144 --> 00:11:19.354
monarch, and what fate awaits anyone who decides to challenge that power.

00:11:20.824 --> 00:11:27.864
And this would be ratcheted up a notch as we move into the late medieval and Tudor periods.

00:11:29.024 --> 00:11:33.534
By the 16th century, England was undergoing huge changes.

00:11:34.254 --> 00:11:38.274
The rise of strong monarchs, like Henry VIII, meant that the

00:11:38.284 --> 00:11:42.074
state’s control over crime and punishment grew even tighter.

00:11:43.113 --> 00:11:49.604
Henry VIII in particular is known for his use of harsh punishments, especially for crimes like

00:11:49.654 --> 00:11:56.014
treason and heresy—offences that threatened his power or the religious authority of the crown.

00:11:56.984 --> 00:12:01.314
If you opposed the king or refused to accept his religious reforms,

00:12:01.634 --> 00:12:05.424
you could find yourself facing the ultimate punishment: execution.

00:12:06.384 --> 00:12:10.954
Beheading, burning at the stake, and hanging, these all became common

00:12:10.954 --> 00:12:14.484
methods of punishment for those who dared to oppose the monarchy.

00:12:15.774 --> 00:12:19.484
These were also times when public punishments were used not

00:12:19.484 --> 00:12:23.444
just to deal with criminals, but to make examples of them.

00:12:24.016 --> 00:12:27.932
Executions were carried out in public squares to send a clear

00:12:27.952 --> 00:12:32.722
message to the population: disobey the king, and this could be you.

00:12:34.342 --> 00:12:37.432
But the state didn’t just rely on execution.

00:12:38.262 --> 00:12:42.492
Other forms of physical punishment, such as whipping and branding,

00:12:42.632 --> 00:12:46.412
where the person would be physically marked for life, were also common.

00:12:47.682 --> 00:12:51.542
And it wasn’t just serious crimes that were punished harshly.

00:12:52.262 --> 00:12:58.182
Minor offences, like theft or begging, were also met with brutal consequences.

00:12:58.652 --> 00:13:03.122
People could be flogged, have their ears cut off, or be thrown into jail.

00:13:04.682 --> 00:13:08.332
But the most infamous period for punishment was yet to

00:13:08.332 --> 00:13:11.962
come—the Bloody Code, which you heard about at the start.

00:13:13.138 --> 00:13:19.068
By the 18th century, the British justice system had become infamous for its severity,

00:13:19.458 --> 00:13:25.028
and there were more than 200 crimes that were technically punishable by death.

00:13:26.388 --> 00:13:32.438
And not just what we would consider today to be serious crimes, like murder or rape.

00:13:33.178 --> 00:13:37.358
Under the Bloody Code, you could also be executed for stealing a sheep,

00:13:37.898 --> 00:13:42.998
cutting down a tree, pickpocketing, if the stolen goods were worth more

00:13:42.998 --> 00:13:48.088
than a shilling, and even for being in the company of Gypsies for one month.

00:13:49.518 --> 00:13:50.903
Why, you might be thinking?

00:13:51.803 --> 00:13:57.373
Justice had been harsh in Britain for hundreds of years, but this seemed particularly

00:13:57.383 --> 00:14:03.763
extreme, just putting one foot wrong could cost a previously upstanding citizen their life.

00:14:04.693 --> 00:14:09.603
Well, the idea behind the Bloody Code was that these harsh punishments

00:14:09.843 --> 00:14:14.613
would act as a deterrent, they would stop people from committing crimes.

00:14:15.753 --> 00:14:19.913
Public executions became even more common, and men,

00:14:20.253 --> 00:14:23.693
women and children were encouraged to come and watch.

00:14:24.713 --> 00:14:28.083
The criminal would be taken through the crowd to the

00:14:28.093 --> 00:14:32.173
gallows, where their crime would be read out for all to hear.

00:14:33.743 --> 00:14:37.583
And these executions were not intended to be quick

00:14:37.723 --> 00:14:41.453
affairs; they were meant to be gruesome public spectacles.

00:14:42.083 --> 00:14:48.003
The condemned would be hanging there kicking and struggling, the idea being that anyone watching

00:14:48.003 --> 00:14:53.483
would think twice about committing a crime, knowing that this would be the fate that awaited them.

00:14:54.643 --> 00:14:56.383
So, did it work?

00:14:57.303 --> 00:14:59.783
In short, no, it did not.

00:15:00.353 --> 00:15:04.293
There is no evidence that crime decreased at all, and some

00:15:04.343 --> 00:15:08.583
evidence to suggest that it actually increased in certain areas.

00:15:10.112 --> 00:15:13.442
As to why, well, there are several theories.

00:15:14.532 --> 00:15:21.402
One is that, like Jean Valjean in France, criminal acts were often done out of necessity.

00:15:22.272 --> 00:15:27.582
People stole because they had no other option, such was the level of poverty in much of the country.

00:15:28.462 --> 00:15:33.852
If you are starving and you have hungry mouths to feed, then you will do whatever is necessary.

00:15:35.272 --> 00:15:41.942
Another theory is that the public nature of the executions often turned executed criminals into

00:15:41.942 --> 00:15:48.002
folk heroes, so the threat of meeting the same fate really wasn’t so much of a threat at all.

00:15:49.877 --> 00:15:54.582
And there was also a growing discomfort, not just among the general

00:15:54.582 --> 00:15:59.102
population but also with those in the justice system responsible for

00:15:59.112 --> 00:16:04.112
administering the law, about the severity and cruelty of the punishments.

00:16:05.252 --> 00:16:10.562
Ending someone’s life for petty theft just felt…wrong, and often

00:16:10.562 --> 00:16:14.112
judges would find a way of avoiding the death penalty, whether that

00:16:14.112 --> 00:16:18.502
was by finding them not guilty or giving them a more lenient sentence.

00:16:20.032 --> 00:16:25.732
In some cases, judges would even sentence a criminal to be hanged, they would be taken

00:16:25.782 --> 00:16:31.482
to the gallows and the noose would be placed around their neck, but then there would be

00:16:31.482 --> 00:16:37.642
a last minute reprieve, a pardon, the idea being that this was to signal to the criminal

00:16:37.972 --> 00:16:43.322
quite how close they had come to death, and it would deter them from doing it again.

00:16:44.729 --> 00:16:48.149
And this growing discomfort with the severity of the

00:16:48.149 --> 00:16:51.789
Bloody Code wasn’t just happening at an individual level.

00:16:52.619 --> 00:16:57.439
The Enlightenment was well underway, and moralists and philosophers

00:16:57.689 --> 00:17:01.699
had started asking questions about the role of the justice system.

00:17:02.969 --> 00:17:06.249
How should a society deal with people who break the law?

00:17:06.839 --> 00:17:09.599
What was the role of the criminal justice system?

00:17:10.159 --> 00:17:13.569
Was it to punish people who had committed a crime, or

00:17:13.739 --> 00:17:16.629
was it to stop crime being committed in the future?

00:17:17.369 --> 00:17:21.269
If it was to punish people who had committed crimes, then surely

00:17:21.279 --> 00:17:24.959
the punishment should be commensurate with the crime committed.

00:17:25.999 --> 00:17:31.427
And if it was to stop future crimes being committed, what did this mean in practice?

00:17:32.027 --> 00:17:36.747
Was it about stopping other people from committing crimes in the future, and therefore

00:17:36.917 --> 00:17:41.527
enforcing harsh and more gruesome public punishments, like during the Bloody Code?

00:17:42.287 --> 00:17:47.458
Or was it about ensuring that the convicted criminal wouldn’t commit crimes in the future?

00:17:48.878 --> 00:17:52.358
And if so, did that mean helping them change their

00:17:52.358 --> 00:17:55.118
character so that they wouldn’t commit future crimes?

00:17:55.468 --> 00:17:57.728
Or did that mean executing them?

00:17:58.248 --> 00:18:03.298
Or did it mean sending them so far away that they wouldn’t be able to commit future crimes?

00:18:04.678 --> 00:18:08.668
Enlightenment thinkers started to analyse the problem from every

00:18:08.668 --> 00:18:13.418
angle, not just from the point of view of how best to reduce crime, but

00:18:13.418 --> 00:18:17.428
also what was the morally and ethically correct way to deal with it.

00:18:18.498 --> 00:18:20.348
Change was on the horizon.

00:18:20.998 --> 00:18:25.238
And in mainland Europe, substantial progress was being made.

00:18:26.670 --> 00:18:30.505
The great Italian Enlightenment philosopher, Cesare Beccaria,

00:18:30.660 --> 00:18:35.750
would publish his seminal work On Crimes and Punishments, in 1764.

00:18:36.988 --> 00:18:41.538
In this, he put forward several controversial arguments, for

00:18:41.538 --> 00:18:45.608
example that the punishment should be proportionate to the crime.

00:18:46.348 --> 00:18:49.993
He also suggested that it was not the severity of the punishment,

00:18:50.600 --> 00:18:54.798
but the certainty of punishment, that would effectively deter crime.

00:18:56.198 --> 00:19:00.278
This was a radical idea at the time, especially in a system that

00:19:00.278 --> 00:19:04.208
believed public executions would stop criminals in their tracks.

00:19:05.604 --> 00:19:10.514
And this shift in thinking laid some important groundwork for a

00:19:10.514 --> 00:19:14.862
slow but significant transformation  of the British legal system.

00:19:16.192 --> 00:19:20.772
Reformers began to speak out against the death penalty for minor crimes,

00:19:21.022 --> 00:19:25.912
and gradually, the number of capital offences started to decline.

00:19:27.262 --> 00:19:32.091
By the early 19th century, transportation—sending convicts to penal

00:19:32.091 --> 00:19:36.721
colonies—had become a more common and popular alternative to execution.

00:19:37.621 --> 00:19:44.691
Now, we actually have an entire episode on Penal Colonies, it’s episode number 108, but to cut a

00:19:44.701 --> 00:19:52.445
long story short, if you committed a crime that once might have led to execution, such as theft or

00:19:52.455 --> 00:19:59.325
forgery, you might now be transported to one of Britain’s distant colonies, typically to Australia.

00:20:00.915 --> 00:20:06.545
Transportation was seen as an effective way to punish the criminal, by sending them to a

00:20:06.575 --> 00:20:11.525
completely new place and meaning that they would never see their friends or family again, and

00:20:11.545 --> 00:20:16.985
also a way of ridding Britain of its criminals, because they were on the other side of the world.

00:20:18.330 --> 00:20:21.610
But transportation wasn’t a perfect solution.

00:20:22.150 --> 00:20:26.950
It was expensive, soon enough word got out that life in Australia wasn’t actually

00:20:26.960 --> 00:20:32.574
all that bad, and getting criminals to Australia and keeping them under control was

00:20:32.574 --> 00:20:37.974
a logistical challenge, and it became a less popular tool in the justice system.

00:20:39.534 --> 00:20:44.424
And at a similar time, so we’re talking the early 19th century here,

00:20:44.924 --> 00:20:49.104
the idea of prison as a form of punishment was gaining traction.

00:20:50.314 --> 00:20:53.094
Now, you might think we have always had prisons,

00:20:53.304 --> 00:20:56.534
but they are actually a relatively recent invention.

00:20:57.901 --> 00:21:01.954
Early prisons in Britain, for example the ones you might see in castles,

00:21:02.434 --> 00:21:06.424
these were often little more than holding cells for people awaiting

00:21:06.424 --> 00:21:10.834
trial or execution, they are more like what we would call “jails” today.

00:21:12.214 --> 00:21:17.074
But with growing discomfort with both the death penalty and transportation,

00:21:17.564 --> 00:21:22.504
there was a shift towards using imprisonment as a punishment in its own right.

00:21:23.894 --> 00:21:27.094
The idea was that this was a place where a criminal could

