reflect on their crimes and become morally reformed.

00:21:32.094 --> 00:21:36.904
And of course, the length they would be required to stay would be proportional to the

00:21:36.914 --> 00:21:42.814
gravity of the crime they had committed, because serious crimes required serious reform.

00:21:44.254 --> 00:21:49.314
Now, we’ll discuss prisons a lot more in part three of this mini-series, but

00:21:49.594 --> 00:21:53.294
the important thing to mention in the context of the history of the British

00:21:53.384 --> 00:21:59.440
justice system is that prison became more about rehabilitation and reintegration

00:21:59.864 --> 00:22:04.584
rather than punishment or removal of undesirable people from society.

00:22:05.554 --> 00:22:11.744
The very word for these early prisons–penitentiaries–gives us a clue to their purpose.

00:22:12.714 --> 00:22:17.874
It comes from the idea of penitence—that criminals should reflect

00:22:17.884 --> 00:22:22.104
on their crimes and become morally reformed while incarcerated.

00:22:23.514 --> 00:22:28.394
At the same time, the idea of solitary confinement was introduced, where

00:22:28.564 --> 00:22:32.924
prisoners were kept in isolation so they could reflect on their crimes.

00:22:33.464 --> 00:22:38.444
It was believed that solitude and silence would lead to moral reformation.

00:22:39.324 --> 00:22:40.734
So did it?

